{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_oliver_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280600532/1930112301/0002.xml":{"full_text":"WEATHER.\n(V. I. Wfathtr Bureau Forecast.)\nFair and colder today; tomorrow fair.\nTemperature*\u2014Highest, 63, at 4 p.m.\nf yesterday; lowest, sl, at midnight.\nFull report on psge 7.\nj\nXT/* 1 Qd/l \"Vz-i 91 filT Entered as second class mattsr\niMO. i>o. 01,011. post offlcs. Washington. D. C.\nWET DEMOCRATIC\nNOMINEE APPEARS\nPROBABLE FOR 1932\nSouthern Drys Insist South to\nBe Solid Again Despite\nRum Issue.\nREPUBLICAN ATTITUDE\nMORE CONTROVERSIAL\nTemperance Forces Threaten Third\nParty Candidate if [Republicans\nFalter on Stand.\nBT O. GOULD LINCOLN.\nDespite promised drives of dry or\nganizations. nomination of a presiden\ntial candidate In 1932 favoring repeal\nor modification of national prohibition\nseems to be the lot of the Democrats two\nyears hence.\nFurthermore, the Democrats are like\nly to write into their party platform a\nplank calling for modification, If not\nactual repeal of the eighteenth amend\nment.\nCanvas of opinion among soms of the\ndryest of the dry members of Senate\nand House from the South brings ad\nmission that such is the situation with\nin the Democratic party.\nWhat the Republicans will do in 1932\nis more controversial, although Chair\nman Fess of the G. O. P. National Com\nmittee has predicted that the party will\nbe found supporting the eighteenth\namendment two years hence. Other\nRepublican politicians, after what hap\npened in the recent elections in Massa\nchusetts. Illinois and Ohio, are Inclined\nto feel that if the party raises the dry\nstandard it will lose States it needs for\nvictory. And still others see stark de\nfeat ahead if the Republicans come out\nfor any kind of modification.\nProsperity May Save O. O. F.\nOne thing may save the Republicans\nand ease the lot of the drys\u2014* return\nof prosperity In the next two years.\nThe Wickers ham Law Enforcement\nCommission gets down to work again\ntomorrow after a 10-day recess on its\nreport on national prohibition. The re\nport cannot, in all probability, be in the\nhands of the President In time for the\ninclusion of the commission\u2019s recom\nmendations in his annual message to\nCongress. The President was hard at\nwork on his message ve*ter lay and\nhopes to have it completed by the mid\ndle of this week.\nReorganization plans for the dry\nforces are under way. with the Anti-\nSaloon League proposing a 13,000,000 to\n$6,000,000 budget and declaring, through\nF. Scott Mc\u00dfride, general eupertotend\nant, that dry candidates must be put\ninto office from the President on down.\nMc\u00dfride said he expected the aidi of\n25,000 business men would be enlisted\nin a campaign of education. He de\nclared that reports of weakening of the\nAnti-Saloon League\u2019s organisation were\n\"bunk.\"\nDr. Clarence True Wilson, general\nsecretary of the Methodist Board of\nTemperance, insisted that the candi\ndates for President in 1932 must be dry,\nwhether Republican or Democrat, to\nobtain the support of his organisation.\nThis Is a rather clear implication that\nif the Republicans falter in their role\nof dry supporters, the dry organisations\nwill seek to put a third-party candidate\nIn the field. Such a candidate could\nscarcely fall to elect the Democratic\nnominee for President.\nSouthern Democrats in Congress,\nspeaking privately for the ssost part,\nInsist that the \"solid South\u2019\u2019 will cleave\nto the Democratic nominee for Presi\ndent in 1932 whether he be wet or dry,\nprovided the religious issue is not again\ninterjected. Many of the Southern\nDemocrats already are looking forward\nto the nomination of Gov. Franklin D.\nRoosevelt of New York at the next\nDemocratic National Convention. If it\nis not to be Roosevelt, then it is likely\nto be Gov. Ritchie of Maryland or Owen\nD. Young of New York, or a wet\nBulkley of Ohio.\nDemocrats Lack a Bryan.\nThese Southern Democrats, who still\nInsist that the South is favorable to\nnational prohibition, point out that they\nhave no longer a William Jennings\nBryan to lead the fight which will be\nwaged against a wet Democratic nom\ninee for the presidency or against a\nmoist, if not a wet plank, in the na\ntional platform. They have no Wood\nrow Wilson to turn to, as they did In\nBaltimore, when Bryan threw his in\nfluence against Champ 'Jla.'k because\nthe Tammany Democrats of New York\nwere favoring Clark. They do have\nSenator \u201cJoe\u201d Robinson, the leader of\nthe Democrats in the Senate, who made\nhis campaign for re-election on a bone\ndry dry platform last Summer. But\nSouthern Democrats still regard the\n(Continued on Page 3, Column 4.)\nSports Highlights\nHarvard's 13-to-0 defeat of a\nstrong Yale team provided the\nmost notable upset of a series on\nthe gridirons of the Nation yes\nterday. others in that class being\nNew Hampshire\u2019s 7-to-0 trouncing\nof Brown; Indiana\u2019s 7-to-6 verdict\nover Purdue\u2019s formidable eleven,\nand the feat of Albright in hold\ning the redoubtable Western\nMaryland aggregation to a 7-to-7\ndraw.\nMichigan, by vanquishing Chi\ncago, 16 to 0, made safe Its Joint\nownership of the Big Ten title\nwith Northwestern, and the lat\nter finally bowed, 0 to 14, to Notre\nDame in a hectic battle that en\nabled Knute Roekne\u2019s Ramblers\nto maintain their unbeaten statu*.\nNavy was hard pressed to obtain\na 6-to-0 victory over Maryland,\nand Georgetown proved unequal\nto the task of stopping Villanova,\nwhich won 13 to 0. Army had an\neasy foe in Ursinus. 18 to 0.\nBoston U. swamped Boston Col\nlege. 47 to 7, and Pordham won I\nhandily from Bueknell, 12 to 0,\nwhile Georgetown\u2019s next foe, De\ntroit U., played a scoreless tie\nwith Michigan State.\nAmong games with traditional\nbackground Washington and Jef\nferson nosed out West Virginia,\n7 to 6; lowa conquered Nebraska,\n12 to 7; Ohio State outpointed\nIllinois, 12 to 9; Lafayette downed\nLehigh, 16 to 6; Wisconsin blanked\nMinnesota. 14 to 0; South Caro\nlina trimmed North Carolina\nState, 19 to 0, and Vanderbilt\ntopped Auburn. 27 to 0.\nDetails of these and other\ngames will be fodnd in the sports\nsection.\nDOAK FAVORED BY PRESIDENT\nFOR NEW SECRETARY OF LABOR\nSelection of Railroad Train\nmen\u2019s Agent Not Finally\nDecided.\nOpposition to Him Will Be\nVoiced by A. F. of L., It Is\nStated.\nBy th. Associated Press.\nWilliam N. Doak of Virginia, editor of\nRailroad Trainman, is favored by Pres\nident Hoover as Secretary of Labor to\nsucceed Senator-elect Davis of Pennsyl\nvania. but a final decision is awaiting\nconsideration of several problems.\nDavis goes to the Senate in another\nweek. While Mr. Hoover has 30 days\nin which to fill the vacancy he and his\nadvisers want the place filled quickly\nin view of the unemployment situation.\nDoak was slated for the original Hoo\nver cabinet two years ago, but the re\nappointment of Secretary Davis was an\nnounced at the last minute.\nShould the President defer selection.\nRobe Carl White, First Assistant Secre\ntary of Labor, likely would hold the of\nfice. White, who is an Indianan, also\nhas been mentioned for Secretary.\nMr. Hoover still has several other\nBAIL UNIONS AGREE\nON SIX-HOUR DAY\nConference With Executives\nPlanned for Unemploy\nment Relief.\nBy the Associated Press.\nCHICAGO. November 22.\u2014Represen\ntatives of five major railway brother\nhoods agreed today, after nearly two\nweeks of conference, to support a pro\npt\u00abal for a six-hour day as a means\nof relieving unemployment in the ranks\nof rail workers.\nA. F. Whitney, president of the\nBrotherhood of Railroad Trainmen,\nmade the announcement on behalf of\nhis colleagues. At the same time a for\nmal statement was issued, presaging a\ngeneral conference of Interests Involved,\nto discuss the shortened day and other\nproposed emergency measures.\nA meeting is to be held at Cleveland\nDecember 4 to work out plans for the\nconference. A long contest before\ndefinite decision on the proposed\nchange in working hours can be made\nwas anticipated by the brotherhood\nexecutives. They adjourned after an\nnouncing their action.\nConference Is Planned.\nThe formal statement said:\n\"Representatives of the Brotherhood\nof Locomotive Engineers, Brotherhood\nof Locomotive Firemen and Enginemen,\nOrder of Railway Conductors, Brother\nhood of Railroad Trainmen and Switch\nmen's Union of North American, who\nhave been in session here to consider\nthe unemployment situation, shorter\nwork day and othe- subjects affecting\nrailroad transportation, adjourned to\nday after appointing a subcommittee of\neach organization with the chief ex\necutives to arrange a general confer\nence of interests involved for the pur\npose of discussing and, if possible,\nagreeing upon measures of relief for\nthe employes and upon a comprehen\nsive program looking to the protection\nof the railroad industry as a whole.\n\"The chief executives have been au\nthorized to take immediate steps to\narrange for the propsed conference and\nwill meet at Cleveland on December 4\nfor this purpose.\u201d\nSubcommittee Make-Up.\nSeven men from each brotherhood\nwere named to make up the subcom\nmittee. The Cleveland meeting, it was\nindicated, would attempt to dispose of\na proposal for a proposed 26-day month,\nwhich had been suggested as an al\nternative. The seven brotherhoods\nclaim a membership of 350,000 out of\n1,500,000 in the 21 unions numbering\nrailway men.\nAfter the Cleveland conference,\nWhitney said, proposals for a changed\nworking day would be submitted to\nrailway executives. If these executives\nrefused to act, the matter would go to\nthe Federal Mediation Board. If no\naction came from that body, the Presi\ndent would be called upon to appoint\nan emergency arbitration board. Lack\ning a dlclsion there. Congress would be\ncalled in.\nThese stetps would be taken in ac\ncordance with the revised railway laws.\nCOUNTER-SUIT FILED\nNational Bank Says \u201cState of\nRussia\u201d o#es Money.\nNEW YORK; November 22 OP).\u2014Not\nonly does the National City Bank deny\nit owes, the \u201cState of Russia\u201d $116,-\n333.05, but it asked judgment today\nfor $4,436,000 in an amended answer to\na suit filed by representatives of the\ndefunct Kerensky government.\nThe Russian litigants charged they\ndeposited the amount sued for with\nthe bank August 13, 1918, through B.\nA. Bakhmeteffe. later succeeded as\nrepresentative of the State of Russia\nin this country by S. Ughet. The bank\nrejoined it had held treasury notes of\nthe State of Russia totaling $4,435,000\nsince May, 1917, demanding judgment\nfor that amount less the sum sued for\nby the Russians.\n\"OLD GLORY\u201d USED AS SIGNAL,\nLEADS TO ARREST ON RUM CHARGE\nFilling Station Proprietor'Said to Have Unfurled Flag\nWhen Whisky Was for Sale,\ny\nMr tbi Associated Press.\nRALENQH, N. C\u201e November 22.\u2014The\npatriotism of Louis Randolph gave\nWake County officers cause for marvel.\nOver his Ailing station there Aoated\nperpetually the Stars and Stripes of\nthe American flag.\nOne peculiarity, however, troubled the\nmen of law. Sometimes the flag Sew\n4\nfEHic JluntLni pfa t.\nWITH DAILY EVENING EDITION\nWASHINGTON, D. C., SUNDAY MORNING, NOVEMBER 23, 1930-120 PAGES.\nWILLIAM N. DOAK.\nnames before him. These include James\nL. Lewis, president of the United Mine\nWorkers of America, and Meyer Bloom\nfeld of New York, a labor expert and\nauthor. William Green, president of\nthe American Federation of Labor, also\nhas been mentioned.\nDoak is the legislative representative\nhere for the Brotherhood of Railroad\nTrainmen and has long been associated\nwith the Trainmen. The organization,\nhowever, is not affiliated with the\nAmerican Federation of Labor.\nDoak is a Republican and supported\n(Continued on Page 2, Column 2.)\nRACKETEER WAR\nGROWS IN GOTHAM\nPolice, Federal Authorities\nand Detectives to Aid U. S.\nDrive.\n\nBy the Associated Press.\nNEW YORK, November 22 \u2014Police\nand Federal authorities joined today\nwith two nationally known private de\ntective agencies in pledging support to\nDistrict Attorney Crain\u2019s effort to\ntransform into open enmity New York\u2019s\nattitude toward racketeers.\nPolice Commissioner Mulrooney of\nfered Crain the services of as many\npolicemen and detectives as are neces\nsary to drive out gangsters who prey\non business, and began to map out the\nwork of police in the war.\nGrand Jury Investigation.\nActing United States Attorney Man\nley announced his support, and United\nStates Attorney Ameli of Brooklyn dis\nclosed that a Federal grand jury had\nbeen investigating racketeering there\nsince the middle of September.\nAmeli said the inquiry had uncov\nered evidence against \u201da number of so\ncalled prominent racketeers and public\nenemies.\u201d\nDistrict Attorney Crain said his call\nto 50 citizens to form a committee of\npublic safety to end racketeering had\nresulted in 50 complaints to him that\nracketeers have Invaded 15 branches of\nbusiness.\nHerbert S. Mosher, general manager\nof the Pinkerton Detective Agency, and\nW. Sherman Bums of the William J.\nBums International Detective Agency,\noffered Crain the services of their or\nganizations, and he accepted.\nAs soon as the complaints which have\ncome in can be put in shape they are\nto be presented to a county grand jury\nJoseph P. Ryan, president of the\nInternational Longshoreman\u2019s Associa\ntion, and a member of the Committee\nof Safety, took issue today mith a com\nplaint to Crain that shippers are in the\nhands of racketeers. Ryan urged an\nInvestigation \u201cso that the Integrity of\nthe steamship interests, the railroad\ncompanies and the loaders on the pier*\nwill not be found guilty without a trial.\u201d\nTWO MURDERED IN TRAP.\nSt. Louis Gang Victims Said to Have\nBeen on Extortion Mission.\nST. LOUIS, November 22 (/P). \u2014Two\nnotorious gunmen and extortionists, said\nby police to have been on their way to\ncollect SI,OOO extortion money, were\ntrapped and murdered by a gangster\nsquad of machine gunners here today.\nThe two men, Lester Barth and\nDewey Goebel, known to have plied\ntheir extortion practices in the under\nworld for some time, to death\n(Continued on Page 2, Column 2.)\nTHOUSANDS SEEK JOBS\nAS PROHIBITION AGENTS\nUncle Sam is having no trouble in\nreceiving thousands of applications\nfrom citizens who are eager to help\nenforce the Volstead law. When the\nreceipt of applications was closed by\nthe Civil Service Commission, 5,860 per\nsons had applied to take the examina\ntions for agents\u2019 jobs in 39 States, Ter\nritories and the District of Columbia.\nThe District of Columbia applicants\nnumber 181, it was announced. Regis\nters of ellgibles already, exist for the\nother States.\nFor deputy prohibition administra\ntor 681 applied throughout the country,\nand 318 others wanted to be employed\nas senior prohibition Investigators.\nThere were 569 applications for the\njob of storekeeper-gauger for the Bu\nreau of Industrial Alcohol.\nIf Congress allows the Attorney Gen\neral the 500 additional agents request\ned, the Civil Service Commission an\nnounced, the places can be filled from\nthe examinations now being held. The\nexamination for agents will be held\nDecember 6 and the one for storekeep\ner-gauger December 3.\nbrilliantly into the wind; again, and\nwith no apparent reason, it was furled.\nThey investigated.\nToday they searched Randolph\u2019s es\ntablishment, found two half-gallon Jars\nand minor receptacles full of whisky\nand arrested Randolph.\nWhen the flag waved, the deputies\nsaid, there was whisky for sale; when\nit was furled* there was none.\n4 DIE IN TRAFFIC;\nDRIVER IS ARRESTED\nIN WOMAN\u2019S DEATH\nTwo Boys Meet Death in\nMotor Cycle Collision\nWith Automobile.\nMOTORIST TELLS POLICE\nHE DID NOT FLEE SCENE\nMiss Mary Kiernan Is Victim and\nMale Companion May Die.\nTwo Others Injured.\nFour persons were killed and two in\njured seriously in a series of traffic ac\ncidents last night and early this morn\ning in the District and nearby Virginia.\nTwo of those killed were 15-year-old\nboys\u2014Howard Kidwell of Fairfax, Va.,\nand Wilbur McDonald of Oakton, Va.\nA third victim was an unidentified col\nored woman, who was struck by an\nautomobile in Arlington County. Va.\nA hit-and-run driver was responsible\nfor the other accident, which resulted\nin the death of Miss Mary Kiernan, 43\nyears old. of 1421 Seventh street, and\nthe serious injury of her companion.\nHarry Helgberger, 45 years old, of 29\nW street.\nWere Crossing Street.\nHeigberger and Miss Kiernan were\ncrossing Rhode Island avenue north\neast at V street about 1:30 o'clock this\nmorning, when they were struck by a*\nmachine which failed to stop. Both\nwere tossed about 10 feet. Miss Kier\nnan died instantly of a fractured skull\nand Heigberger was taken to Emergency\nHospital in a dying condition.\nAt 3 o\u2019clock this morning George\nWarren Graham, 29. of 69 Rhode Island\navenue, called police and reported he\nbelieved he had been in an accident on\nRhode Island avenue. He was arrested\nand taken to No. 12 precinct station,\nwhere police said he admitted hitting\nthe man and woman, but that he did\nnot flee from the scene. He said he\nstopped and helped bystanders place\nthem into a cab. No charge had been\npreferred against him.\nAnother hit-and-run driver was re\nsponsible for the second serious injury,\nthe victim being Louis Honesdy, colored,\n29 years old, of Vienna. Va. He was\nstruck while crossing Key Bridge, and\ntaken to Georgetown University Hospital\nwith compound fractures of the legs and\nother injuries.\nThe two boys. Kidwell and McDon\nald, were killed instantly about 8 o'clock\nlast night, when a motor cycle on which\nthey were riding collided on the Chain\nBridge road near Oakton with an auto\nmobile driven by George W. Johnson\nof Glen Echo. Md.\nThe impact of the collision tore off\none side of Johnson's car and the\nshattered glass severely cut his wife\nand Raymond Cook who were in the\nmachine with him. Three young chil\ndren of Mr. and Mrs. Johnson, who also\nwere in the car, escaped Injury.\nMrs. Johnson and Cook were taken\nto Georgetown University Hospital for\ntreatment. Their injuries are not con\nsidered serious.\nCollide at Turn in Road.\nThe accident occurred at a sharp\nturn in the road. Johnson told Fairfax\nCounty police that when he saw the\nmotor cycle approaching on the curve\nhe did not have time to swerve his car\nto avoid the collision.\nKidwell and McDonald were riding\na motor cycle owned by John Bell of\nOakton. son of Mr. and Mrs. Hugh\nBell. The boys had borrowed it for a\ntrip to Vienna and collided with John\nson\u2019s car about five minutes after leav\ning Bell\u2019s home.\nEarlier in the evening Bell had driven\nthe motor cycle to Fairfax to visit Kid\nwell. who lived there with his widowed\nmother and his sister and brother-in\nlaw. Mr. and Mrs. George King Davis.\nKidwell later returned to Oakton with\nBell and loaned the two boys his motor\ncycle when he went to visit a girl,\ntaking the Bell family car.\nThe bodies of Kidwell and McDonald\nwere removed to Money's undertaking\nestablishment in Vienna, where an in\nquest was conducted by Coroner C. A\nRansom.\nMcDonald\u2019s father is employed In the\npress room of the Fairfax Herald.\nCREW SAFIfAS BUMP\nCRASHES IN ALABAMA\nBubber Company's Craft Vigilante\nWrecks on Mountain Side;\nCause Not Yet Known.\nBy the Associated Press.\nPIEDMONT, Ala., November 22.\nThe baby blimp, Vigilante, owned by\nthe Goodyear Tire Rubber Co. of\nAkron. Ohio, was wrecked on Smoky\nMountain, three miles east of here to\nday. Her crew of three escaped with\nout injury.\nAlternate Pilot R. N. Crosier reported\nthe accident to Goodyear officials, but\ndeclined to discuss it. He said he was\ninstructed to answer no questions pend\ning an investigation. Crosier was ac\ncompanied by Pilot Paul Long, in charge\nof the blimp, and Mechanic James S.\nPoyles. A short time before the\nblimp crashed into a tree atop Bmoky\nMountain the ship had been sailing over\nthis town.\nFarmers living in the vicinity of the\naccident saw the ship smash.\nLeonard Gordon, representative of\nthe Goodyear plant in Atlanta, said\nthere was no explosion nor fire from the\naccident.\np. W. Litchfield, president of the\nGoodyear Co., was in Atlanta waiting\nfor the return of the craft on which he\nwas to be a passenger on its return\nflight to Akron.\nGoodyear officials in Atlanta said the\nship cost $60,000 to construct.\nA CHARMING LOVE\nSTORY LAID IN A\n\u2022TLJC CCTD CT A r delightful s et-\nIMt Ur TINa with a plot\nMARGARET YORKE\"\nSUSPENSE AND SUR\nBY PRISES. DON\u2019T FAIL\nTO READ THIS MOV\nKATHLEEN NORRIS story by one j\nOF AMERICA\u2019S MOST\nFAMOUS NOVELISTS.\ni 1\nBEGINNING IN MONDAY'S STAR\nrk\u2014 r\u2014l\nP\nDOCTOR SHOOTS SELF WHILE\nDRIVING CAR IN CITY TRAFFIC\nAuto With Body of Former G. W. U.\nStudent Slumped Over Wheel Crashes\nInto Another Machine.\nDr. Luther Buehler, 33-year-old for\nmer George Washington University\nstudent, shot himself in the mouth with\na .44-callber revolver as he drove his\nautomobile along crowded upper Four\nteenth street in the vicinity of Park\nroad last night. Dying almost instantly,\nhe slumped over the steering wheel of\nhis machine as it continued up Four\nteenth street, and crashed into the car\nof Louis Gotthold of 614 Fifth street\nnortheast, who had been stopped at the\nintersection of Fourteenth and Monroe\nstreets by a red signal light.\nBuehler shot himself as scores of per\nsons were coming out of the Tivoli\nCHILD CONFERENCE\nLAYS BROAD BASE\nWhite House Delegates Work\nOut Details for Protection\nand Advancement.\nLeaving behind them a broad basic\nprogram\u2014medical, educational, social\nand economic\u2014for the Nation\u2019s 45,000,-\n000 children, the White House Con\nference on Child Health and Protection\nended its work yesterday.\nThe final reports of the committees,\nwhich embraced extensive special re\nsearches during the past year and went\ninto every phase of American child life\nfrom the first cry to physical and men\ntal maturity, were adopted as modified\nand amended during the sessions here\nthis week.\nLooking into the future the commit\ntees saw a vision of the America of the\nnext generation, its citizenship affected\nboth favorably and adversely by the\nsocial trends of the present. Acting on\nthe text of Secretary Wilbur's statement\nthat \u201cour only permanent possession is\nlife\u201d, the scientists and educators who\nmade up the conference saw clear possi\nbilities of more life and richer living.\nMediocre Danger Seen.\nBut they also visioned the danger of\na deadening mediocrity of citizenship\nresulting from the increasing standardi\nzation of schools and homes, and the\nIncreasing littleness of the Individual in\nthe face of the machine.\nThe final report was an uncompro\nmising statement of the absolute rights,\nnot special privileges, of every Amer\nican child now living.\nThe conclusions were summarized by\nSecretary Wilbur last night in the Na\ntional Radio Forum arranged by The\nStar and broadcast over a Nation-wide\n(Continued on Page 4, Column 6.)\nrhinFimperils cities\nDisastrous Flood Threatened as\nTributaries Rise.\nCOLOGNE, Germany, November 22\n(/P).\u2014Tributaries of the Rhine poured\nhuge masses of water down the Rhine\nValley tonight and the Rhine adminis\ntration declared a state of emergency\nas disastrous floods threatened.\nDwellings near the river have been\nevacuated, three electric power houses\nnear Frankfort-on-Maln were disabled\nand near Heidelberg several quarries\nwere under water tonight.\nThe Moselle River has overflowed at\nseveral points and at the village of\nLudweiler a dam burst and inundated\nthe community\nTheater, but none of them saw him\nor noticed the car with its dead driver\nslowly moving along Fourteenth street.\nWhen the automobile hit Gotthold's car,\nGotthold drew over to the curb and\nwaited for the expected apologies. But\nthe other machine did not move. Gott\nhold got out of his car and investi\ngated. He saw Buehler\u2019s body slumped\nover the steering wheel, a gun clutched\nin his right hand.\nPolice immediately were notified, and\nBuehler was taken to Garfield Hospital.\nThe body was there for nearly an hour\nbefore it was identified by William K.\nWade, who roomed with Beuhler at 1915\nI street.\nWade was questioned by Detective\n(Continued on Page 2, Column 7.)\nTIME BOMBISSENT\nTO A P. IN SPOKANE\nLocksmiths and Correspond\nent Dismantle Dynamite\nand Prevent Blast.\nBy the Associated Press.\nSPOKANE. Wash., November 22.\u2014A\ntime dynamite bomb balieved capable\nof blasting a city block was delivered\nto the Associated Press office here\ntoday and was taken apart by lock\nsmiths and an Associated Press em\nployee 2 hours before the time clock\nwas set to go off.\nThe bomb, placed in a steamer trunk\nand attached to an electric battery and\na time clock was delivered to the Asso\nciated Press this morning by the Ameri\ncan Railway Express Company.\nCleveland Williams, Associated Press\ncorrespondent, checked and ascertained\nthe senders names were faked and this\nafternoon took the trunk to a lock\nsmith. The smith opened the trunk\nand Williams ripped the bomb apart.\nTwo years ago a dynamite bomb was\nleft in the entrance to the Spokesman-\nReview building which houses the As\nsociated Press office. The fuse died out\nwithout igniting.\nTraceN to Seattle.\nThe trunk was delivered bearing tags\nwhich Indicated it was sent from\nSeattle. The sender\u2019s name on the ad\ndress tag was \u201cAmericus Vespucias,\nGenoa, Indiana.\u201d Another tag bearing\nthe name of the Seattle Transfer Com\npany, from which the claim check had\nbeen tom, bore the name of M. C.\nMalley, Room 309, Bush Hotel. It was\nnumbered 84083. A notification card\n(Continued on Page 2, Column 1.)\nWINDSTORM* HITS PARIS\nNumber of Persons Reported Hurt\nby Falling Debris.\nPARIS, November 23 (Sunday) OP).\nA violent windstorm struck Paris just\nafter Midnight, with reports from vari\nous parts of the city showing that a\nconsiderable number of persons were in\njured by falling chimneys and scaffold\nings of buildings under construction.\nThe storm struck Just as the theaters\nwere closing, and the cases filled quickly\nwith persons hunting refuge.\nAt the same time additional reports\nwere received of damage caused in\nNorthern France by heavy rains. A\nfarmer\u2019s house near Amiens was partly\ndemolished by a landslide, and the\nlower sections of Llsieux were under\nwater.\nWIFE\u2019S UNANSWERED CALL LEADS\nRESCUE OF MAN FROM DEATH\nGoing to Garage to Investigate, She Finds Husband\nOvercome by Gas.\nBecause his wife prepared dinner a 1\nfew minutes earlier than usual last\nnight Kenneth Skinner. 48-year-old i\nbutcher, of 3607 Warder street, Is alive i\ntoday.\nSkinner went to his garage last eve- t\nnlng to make a few repairs to his auto- i\nmobile. i\nWhen the family dinner was ready a\nlittle earlier than usual. Mrs. Skinner 1\nwent to the back door and called him.\nReceiving no response, she went to the\ngarage, opened the door, and found\nFIVE CENTS TEN CENTS\nIN WASHINGTON AND SUBURBS ELSEWHERE\nTIGHT VOTE FACES\nREAPPORTIONMENT\nCity Versus Country Clash on\nHouse Change Faces\nComplications.\nBY WILL P. KENNEDY.\nThe reapportionment light which\nlooms lor the incoming short session\nthreatens as close a decision as the\nparty organisation of the new Congress\nsome 13 months hence. Here also the\nsmall \"third party\" or neutrals are\nfound holding the deciding votes.\nAll this is disclosed in an analysis\nmade by an official of the House for\nthe Republican leadership to guide Its\npolicy In the matter.\nAs the situation now stands reappor\ntionment becomes automatic after the\nincoming short session has passed into\nhistory, unless some amendatory action\nis taken. This would affect the Con\ngress to be elected In the Pall of 1932.\nFenn Friend of DeaL\nWith Connecticut gaining one seat\nunder the census figures, which are to\nbe the basis for reapportionment. Rep\nresentative E. Hart Fenn of Connecti\ncut. who is chairman of the House\nCensus Committee, sees little likelihood\nof any action to annul or modify the\nlegislation already passed. He will do\nall in his power to prevent action by\nhis committee to report out any such\nbill.\nNevertheless there will be plenty of\nmeasures Introduced seeking to change\nthe reapportionment act. Members\nfrom the Middle West and the South,\nheading an anti-alien movement, will\nseek to have the aliens eliminated from\nthe census figures to be used as a basis\nof apportioning representation in the\nHouse, with the claim that some 7,-\n500,000 aliens are now counted in with\nAmerican citizens in figuring out an\n\"equal voice\u201d for all citizens in legisla\ntion. With the industrial cities Jam\nmed with alien workers this promises to\ndevelop into a city versus country clash.\nWould Bar Colored.\nThen, again, legislation aimed to ex\nclude colored persons who are not al\nlowed to vote in the South is to be\nurged by Representative George Holden\nTlnkham of Massachusetts. So, much\nas Chairman Fenn. with the gain for\nhis home State well in mind, may try\nto prevent legislation on this subject\nthere are many other members who will\nmake a stubborn fight for the change\nwhich would prevent the present law\nfrom going into operation.\nParty leaders emphasize that the\nchances are against any corrective leg\nislation being passed at the Incoming\nshort session on the general theory that\nit would have been much easier to head\noff the reapportionment before the act\nwas passed than it will be now to get\nthrough by affirmative action any meas\nure that would tend to nullify the ex\nisting law.\nThe analysis for the House leaders,\nhowever, shows that if the objectors,\nthose seeking amendment of the law to\nprevent a reapportionment on the basis\nof the new census returns, do manage\nto get the bill out of committee, the\nline-up for a vote in the House will be\none of the closest in history.\nClose Vote Possible.\nThis analysis shows the numerical\nstrength of delegations in the House.\nSeventy-first Congress, of States which\nwould gain through use of the present\ncensus figures to be 161; while the State\n(Continued on Page 2, Column 6.)\nSLAY FOR INSURANCE\nWife and Brother Confess Plot for\n92,000 Stake.\nPHILADELPHIA, November 22\nMrs. Clarence Grace Prophet and her\nbrother, Harold Wllliaihs, police an\nnounced tonight, confessed to having\nkilled William F. Prophet, the woman\u2019s\nhusband, to obtain $2,000 life insurance,\ntaken out several months ago.\nhim unconscious under the machine.\nThe garage was filled with carbon\nmonoxide gas from the exhaust of the\near.\nUnable to remove him herself, she i\nsummoned neighbors who carried Skin\nner Into tbs nous*. The fire depart-!\nment rescue squad was staled and after\nsome minutes succeeded reviving!\nhim.\nHad Skinner been left in the garage I\na little longer, they said, it wool* have\n\u201cFrom Press to Homo\nWithin the Hour\nThe Star la delivered every evening and\nSunday morning to Washington homes by\nThe Btar's exclusive carrier sendee. Phone\nNational 8000 to start Immediate delivery.\nC4*) Means Associated Press.\nSOVIET PRODUCTS\nWOULD RE BARRED\nBY PROPOSED RULE\nTreasury Officials Refer Draft\nto Customs Bureau for\nModification.\nAMERICAN IMPORTERS\nOFFER VIGOROUS PROTEST\nWhile Regulation Is General It\nWould Place Permanent Em\nbargo on Eussian Goods.\nBY THEODORE C. WALLEN.\nAgitation over Russian trade with\nAmerican Interests has broken out anew\nwith the disclosure that Treasury au\nthorities have drafted a proposed new\nregulation which In effect would exclude\nSoviet products from the United States.\nIn the face of vigorous protest from\nAmerican Importers, the original draft\nas laid before high Treasury officials\nhas been referred back to the Customs\nBureau for such modification aa is pos\nsible \"without Impairing the effect\nsought.\u201d\nFollowing the Treasury\u2019s embargoes\nlast Bummer on Russian pulpwood,\nlumber and other products, it tran\nspires, experts of the department were\nset to work drawing up a ruling which\nwould overcome the obstacles to ex\nclusion which were encountered at\nthat time. The product of that effort\nwas a draft which would provide that,\nupon the complaint of any cltisen, the\nTreasury would put an embargo on any\nshipment arriving at an American port\nwhich embargo would remain In effect\nuntil all of the following requirements\nhad been met:\n1. The filing of a bond covering the\nvalue of the cargo.\n2. The production of a consular in\nvoice.\nI. Presentation of definite proof that\nthe cargo contained no goods made i- 1\nwhole or In part by convict labor.\nApplies to All Countries.\nWhile the regulation would bo genera!\nIn nature, that Is, applying equally to\nImports from any country, the effect\nwould be to put a permanent embargo\non Soviet roods, since cargoes clearing\nfrom Russian ports could not qualify\nunder all three conditions.\nThe fact that the Treasury was un\nable to prove that certain Soviet\nlumber cargoes represented convict\nlabor forced the lifting of embargoes\nlast Summer by Seymour Lowman, As\nsistant Secretary of the Treasury In\ncharge of customs.\nUnder the bro Dosed ruling, not only\nwould the burden of proof be shifted\nto the Importer and hence to the Soviet\ngovernment, but Russian roods would\nbe barred in any event by tne re\nauirement of a consular, visa. Since\ntie United States has no relations with\nRussia and hence no consuls there,\nconsular invoices would be unavailable\nto Amtorg, the Russian trading cor\nporation In the United States.\nImporters Raise Pretest.\nAmerican Importers and shipping in\nterests standing to be affected by such\na ruling learned of the proposed rul\ning, which they attributed largely to\nMr. Lowman, and raised energetic pro\ntest. It was pointed out that the\nUnited States, by Imposing such \"dis\ncriminatory restrictions,\u201d would risk the\ncomplete cessation of Russian pur\nchases In this country, which in the\nfirst eight months of this year have\nreached a total of $89,738,006 as against\nImports valued at $16,529,369.\nThe draft had been forwarded, mean\ntime, through the regular channels to\nthe office of Andrew W. Mellon, Sec\nretary of the Treasury. For some time,\naccording to Treasury officials, it was\nin the hands of Secretary Mellon\u2019s spe\ncial counsel In the department, and\nthen went back to the Customs Bureau.\nIn explanation of the delay, Mr. Low\nman yesterday said \"it was felt that\nthe regulation, as drafted, might be\ntoo drastic, and therefore it is now\nbeing reviewed by the Customs Bureau\nto see if any modification is possible\nwithout impairing the effect sought.\u2019\u2019\nHe emphasized that the Treasurv was\ndoing nothing more than to carry out\na provision of the tariff act which re\nquires the Treasury to promulgate such\nregulations as will shut out products of\nconvict labor and, after next year,\nproducts of forced labor. But It had\nto be done by general regulation, he\n(Continued on Page 2, Column f.)\nTODAY\u2019S STAR\nPART ONE\u201432 PAGES.\nGeneral News\u2014Local, National and\nForeign.\nEducational News\u2014Page B-S.\nArmy and Navy News\u2014Page C-8.\nPART TWO\u2014B PAGES.\nEditorials and Editorial Features.\nAt Community Centers\u2014Page 6.\nPART THREE\u2014I 3 PAGES.\nSociety Section.\nPART FOUR\u2014IO PAGES.\nAmusement Section\u2014Theater, Screen\nand Radio.\nIn the Motor World\u2014Page 4.\nDistrict of Columbia Naval Reserve-\nPage 5.\nAmerican Legion\u2014Page 5.\nGirl Scouts\u2014Page 5.\nW. C. T. U. Notes\u2014Page 8.\nSerial Story, \"The Scarab Murder\nCase\u201d\u2014Page 